  "case_id": "D2N132",
  "method": "direct",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nBack pain following a fall at a surprise birthday party.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports back pain following a fall while hiding during a surprise birthday party. He describes twisting his back while attempting to stand up and hitting the staircase railing. He denies radicular symptoms or leg pain. He reports some stiffness with rotation and increased pain with prolonged lying flat. He has a history of lumbar fusion performed previously. He currently takes ibuprofen for pain and takes medication for anxiety.\n\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals tenderness to palpation of the lumbar paraspinal muscles. Range of motion is limited by pain with rotation. Neurological examination is unremarkable, with intact sensation and motor strength in the lower extremities. The x-ray demonstrates healing from a previous lumbar fusion at L4, without evidence of acute fractures or compression fractures.\n\nAssessment\nLow back strain secondary to acute injury.\n\nPlan\nPrescribe ibuprofen 800 mg three times daily with food. Recommend ice and heat alternating on the lumbar region. Encourage ambulation. Schedule a follow-up appointment in one week if symptoms do not improve or worsen.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nBack pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Lee is a 40-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of back pain. She states she was at a birthday party and she ran her back into the railing of the staircase and twisted her back. She denies any pain radiating down her legs. Lying flat and twisting motions aggravate the pain. She is currently taking ibuprofen.\n\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS:\n\nIbuprofen.\n\nPAST MEDICAL HISTORY:\n\nAnxiety.\n\nPAST SURGICAL HISTORY:\n\nLumbar fusion\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the back shows range of motion without pain. Straight leg raise is negative. Sensation is intact.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the lumbar spine show no obvious signs of acute fracture. Evidence of a prior lumbar fusion with hardware in good position.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nLumbar spine strain.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended ice and heat. She will continue with Motrin 800 mg 3 times a day with food. She will follow up with me as needed.",
